Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

Exercise 1.1. Which mobile food vendor(s) sells at the most locations?

In this question, the food vendor moves from time to time and we can measure its movement by locationid. To get the mobile food vendor that sells at the most locations, we count the number of unique locationid by permit and then inner join the permit table to get permit's owner. Therefore, the mobile food vendor that sells at the most locations is May Catering's with permit 17MFF-0110.

You should try to come up with some questions on your own, but these are examples of reasonable questions:

  • Which parts of the city are the most and least expensive?
  • Which parts of the city are the most dangerous (and at what times)?
  • Are noise complaints and mobile food vendors related?
  • What are the best times and places to find food trucks?
  • Is there a relationship between housing prices and any of the other tables?

Please make sure to clearly state each of your questions in your submission.

Questions:

1. What time has the most frequent criminal cases? Plot the location to see where those cases are.

In order to know which datetime has the most frequent criminal cases, I grouped the crime table by datetime and ordered by frequency. As we can see, every year's 01/01 00:01:00 is the most frequent time among the top frequent crimial cases' list, especially at 2011-01-01 00:01:00 with 185 cases.

As we look at those cases at the time of 2011-01-01 00:01:00, most of the cases are: non-criminal offenses, sex offenses, assault, theft and vandalism. One possible reason why there are a lot of criminal cases happened at this time is that on New Year's Eve, a lof of people go out and have fun, which gives criminals chances to commit crimes and in a crowded place, criminals have a higher chance to succeed. Also, in a relaxed environment, people's vigilance goes down, which also lead to the increase of criminal cases.

As we plot the locations of criminals happened on 2011-01-01 00:01:00, we can see that the northeast part of San Francisco has more crinimal cases.

2. Which part of the city has the most criminal cases occured?

I used the crime table to find which part of the city has the most criminal cases. I first counted the number of criminal cases group by each district to get an overall impression of the crime distribution in San Francisco. We can see that Southern District has the most number of crime cases, about 6,000 cases more comparing to the second place, Mission district; and 7,000 cases more comparing to the third place, Northern District. This result is not surprising, since the top three district are located around downtown San Francisco, downtown areas usually would have more criminal cases occur. Richmond District and Park District has the least criminal cases, almost comparing to Southern District, of course, those are high income residential area, therefore it is reasonable to have lower crimes. There is one crime case does not have location record in the dataset. The type of crime that appears the most in Southern District is larceny and theft, the second place is non-criminal cases. The above is a choropleth map in respect to numbers of crime for each district. Darker color represents more crimes in that region.

The reason to use a choropleth map instead of a heat map for this question is that a choropleth map can color a specific region like district region; while a heat map can only put points in a specific location. I plotted 500 crime locations from the crime table, the aggregate number appears as a circle marker on the map. As you zoom in, the marker will split into to a smaller maker with a more precise number to represent the number of crimes in that area. Makers with large number appears in a darker region, this is once again consistent with the previous conclusion. Overall, the downtown area of San Francisco is the most dangerous region.

3. Are public schools and private schools distributed differently across the city?

I used the school table to answer this question. I grouped the data by public and private school and used two heat maps to plot the locations of each type of school. The advantage of using a heat map for this problem is that it can tell the concentrate of a clustering points. If there are more points in that region, the color will be darker. It can visually tell where each type of schools is concentrating into; while comparing to a choropleth map which can only tell the number of schools in a whole piece of region.

From the above result, we can see that public schools are more concentrated in Mission District and Northern District, fewer public schools appear other than those two districts. On the other hand, private schools are everywhere across San Francisco, except in those recreational parks.

We can conclude that public schools and private schools distributed differently across the city, one reason to explain this circumstance would be the limiting education funding of the city. The city education department has a shortage of funding to run more public schools, while comparing to private school owners have more fiscal advantages to operate an educational organization.

4. What time has the most noise complains? Are noise complaints and mobile food vendors related?

I firstly used the noise table to get the datetime and complaint frequency, and then plot the complaint frequency by time and day. From the plot we can see that the top number of complaints happens at Friday 22-23 and Saturday 22-24 o'colck. The possible interpretation is that people are having a party during the weekend. Another possible interpretation is that the owners are moving the mobile food vendors back to home, which may cause the noise.

In order to investigate if the noise complaints and mobile food vendors are related, I plotted the choropleth map of San Francisco city differentiated by the number of noise complaints. Regions with large number of noise complaints are in dark color, while regions with small number of noise complaints are in light color. Number of mobile food vendors in a specific region are clustered together. Dark red clusters indicate the large number of mobile food vendors in this region, while light green clusters indicate the small number of mobile food vendors in this region.

Intuitively, we may possess the idea that quiet places will have more mobile food vendors and noisy places will have less mobile food vendors, or vice versa. However, the map does not support either idea. Suppose that we want to know whether there is a negative relation between the noisiness of a neighborhood and the number of mobile food vendors. Under this assumption, we would like to see less mobile food vendors in noisier neighborhoods. From the map, we can observe that mobile food vendors are mainly distributed on the right wing of the city, and there are not many of them on the left wing. For the large number of mobile food vendors on the right wing, more are distributed closer to shore. That is, mobile food vendors are more distributed in neighborhoods like South of Market, Financial Districts, Potrero Hill, and Hunter's Point. These neighborhoods have a range of noise complaints from 78 to 241, which are not recognized as quiet places. The quietest neighborhoods, such as Sunset District, Richmond District and Lake Merced, have least number of mobile food vendors. Clearly, the map does not support this idea, and we conclude that noise complaints and mobile food vendors are not related.

Although not related to the noisiness of the neighborhood, the number of mobile food vendors is more likely related to the flow of people. Neighborhoods like South of Market and Financial District have huge flow of people, either people at work or tourists. Presumedly, it is these types of people that mobile food vendors target for.

# Load the noise table and remove NAs
noise_time = pd.read_sql("SELECT Datetime FROM noise", db).dropna(subset = ['Datetime'])
date_time = pd.DataFrame([i.split(" ") for i in noise_time['Datetime']])
date_time.columns = ['date','time']

def day_of_week(date):
    '''
    Given a data and return a corresponding year, month and day
    Input:
        year-month-day
    Output:
        year, month, day (integer)
    '''
    year, month, day = (int(x) for x in date.split('-'))    
    time = datetime.date(year, month, day)
    # Sunday is 0, Monday is 1 
    time =  time.strftime("%w")
    return time

# Add the corresponding date, time, week
dayofweek = [int(day_of_week(i)) for i in date_time['date']]
date_time['dayofweek'] = dayofweek
date_time['time'] = [i.split(":")[0] for i in date_time['time']]
date_time = date_time.sort_values(by = 'dayofweek')

def plotCounts(dataframe, xlabel_name, ylabel_name):
    
    sf_neighborhood = json.load(open(os.getcwd() + '/SanFrancisco.Neighborhoods.json'))
    neighborhoods = {str(feature[u'id']): str(feature[u'properties'][u'neighborhood']) 
                     for feature in sf_neighborhood[u'features']}
    
    dataframe_groupby_zip = list(dataframe.groupby("zip"))
    dataframe_zips = [str(i[0]) for i in dataframe_groupby_zip]
    dataframe_zip_count = {dataframe_zips[i]: len(dataframe_groupby_zip[i][1]) 
                           for i in xrange(len(dataframe_groupby_zip))}
    dataframe_zip_count = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(dataframe_zip_count, orient = "index")
    dataframe_zip_count.columns = ["Count"]
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 5), dpi = 100)
    
    colors = sns.color_palette("YlOrRd", len(dataframe_zip_count))
    colors = colors[::-1]
    
    plot_dataframe_count = sns.barplot(x = dataframe_zip_count.index, 
                                       y = dataframe_zip_count.Count, palette = colors, 
                                       order = list(dataframe_zip_count.sort_values(by = "Count", 
                                                                                    ascending = False).index))
    for tick in plot_dataframe_count.get_xticklabels():
        tick.set_rotation(-45)
    
    plot_dataframe_count.set(xlabel = "{}".format(xlabel_name), ylabel = "Number of {}".format(ylabel_name), 
                         title = "Number of {} by {}".format(ylabel_name, xlabel_name))
    
    return plot_dataframe_count

5. Is the number of schools positively correlated to the housing price in a certain neighborhood?

For this question, if the assumption holds, we will see more schools in an expensive neighborhood compared to the number of schools in an inexpensive neighborhood. However, this is not entirely true. Consider the moderately dark blue regions in the middle of the map. Those neighborhoods are Twin Peaks, Noe Valley and The Castro, respectively. The clusters representing the number of schools in the neighborhood are green, which indicates the number of schools is relatively low. However, in neighborhoods such as Sunset District, Richmond District and Lake Merced, some clusters are yellow, indicating a moderately high number of schools in the neighborhood. Despite this observation, neighborhoods like Pacific Heights and Nob Hill, where median house sold price is in the range from 565 to 637, are concerntrated with more schools. In short, the statement that more schools exist in more expensive neighborhoods holds partially correct.

From the discussion above, we conclude that the statement holds true in some neighborhoods, while not true in other neighborhoods. A more general statement involving the number of schools and the housing price would be: the number of schools depends on the number of local residents in that neighborhood. While some neighborhood are more expensive regarding the housing price, the housing price is determined by the market.
